Great comparison 👌 — both look similar, but they’re actually very different concepts.
Here’s how to explain the difference clearly (and interview-ready).

Program 1: Fixed (pure) currying
function sum(a){
  return function (b){
    return function(c){
      return function(d){
        return a + b + c + d;
      }
    }
  }
}

console.log(sum(1)(2)(3)(4)); // 10

What this is

✅ Pure / fixed currying

Key characteristics

Fixed number of arguments (4)

One function per argument

Stops automatically after the last argument

No special stop condition needed

No recursion

How it works

Each function stores its value via closure

Final function computes and returns the result

When to use

When the number of parameters is known in advance

Functional programming patterns

Program 2: Infinite / variadic currying
let sum = function (a) {
  return function (b) {
    if (b !== undefined) {
      return sum(a + b);
    }
    return a;
  };
}

console.log(sum(1)(2)(3)(4)()); // 10

What this is

✅ Infinite (dynamic) currying using recursion

Key characteristics

Unlimited number of arguments

Uses recursion

Requires an explicit termination ()

Accumulates result step by step

How it works

Each call creates a new closure with updated a

Stops only when no argument is passed

When to use

When the number of arguments is not known

Chainable APIs (like sum(1)(2)(3)...)

🔍 Side-by-side comparison
Feature	Program 1	Program 2
Arguments	Fixed (4)	Unlimited
Currying type	Pure / fixed	Infinite / variadic
Uses recursion	❌ No	✅ Yes
Stop condition	Automatic	Explicit ()
Flexibility	Low	High
Interview label	“Currying”	“Currying + Closure + Recursion”
🧠 One-line interview answer

If they ask “difference between these two?” say:

“The first example is fixed currying with a known number of arguments, while the second example is infinite currying using recursion and closures, where arguments can be passed dynamically and the chain stops explicitly.”

Bonus insight (interview brownie points 🍪)

“The second approach is more flexible but slightly less readable, while the first is cleaner when arity is known.”